Insufficient Response Analysis

Initial setup

Import the eavehelpers package we have locally, plus any extra packages that we need for making plots etc.

library(eavehelpers)
library(ggplot2)
library(phsstyles)

Load Data

See notebook called ‘LoadData.Rmd’ for how the analysis dataframes were created:

data.pc <- readRDS("/conf/EAVE/GPanalysis/data/temp/fail_to_mount_pc_Jan13_final.rds")
data.bd <- readRDS("/conf/EAVE/GPanalysis/data/temp/fail_to_mount_bd_Jan13_final.rds")
print (nrow(data.pc))
[1] 23938
print (nrow(data.bd))
[1] 22499

Create an output folder for the date we are running the analysis.

output_folder <- file.path("results","FINAL")# Sys.Date())
dir.create(output_folder, showWarnings = TRUE)
'results/FINAL' already exists

Model A

Build analysis dataframes for the two cohorts that we’ll use for model of type-A. We use the helper functions that take the input dataframes from the cohorts we build and they do some extra data cleaning and coding of variables (mostly it is just converting variables into factor variables that are convienent to use the the GAM fits to calculate ORs with)

pc.modelA.df <- eavehelpers::get_modelA_df(data.pc)
bd.modelA.df <- eavehelpers::get_modelA_df(data.bd)

Get variables to use in the models

Perform a check on the confounding variables we want to use for modelA… This function returns the names of the variables that pass the univariable logit glm test fit for the outcome variable

pc.modelA.vars <- pc.modelA.df %>% 
                  select(insufficient_response,prior_infection,
                         simd2020v2_sc_quintile,immuno,shielding,ch_resident) %>% 
                  eavehelpers::get_vars_to_use(outcome_var='insufficient_response')
print (pc.modelA.vars)
[1] "prior_infection"        "simd2020v2_sc_quintile" "immuno"                 "shielding"             
[5] "ch_resident"

Doing this for the blood donors shows how it helps to remove the usage of the ch_resident variable. Expected as we shouldn’t really be getting care-home residents that are also blood donors.

bd.modelA.vars <- bd.modelA.df %>% 
                  select(insufficient_response,prior_infection,
                         simd2020v2_sc_quintile,immuno,shielding,ch_resident) %>% 
                  eavehelpers::get_vars_to_use(outcome_var='insufficient_response')
print (bd.modelA.vars)
[1] "prior_infection"        "simd2020v2_sc_quintile" "immuno"                 "shielding"

Construct formulas for the models

Build up a formula to use for the GAM fit for primary care attendees …

pc.modelA.gam.formula <- paste0(
  "insufficient_response ~ ", #outcome varialbe
  " s(age,by=cat,k=5) + cat", #age is a spline stratified by cat (product-dose categories)
  " + s(days_since_first_measurement) ", #spline of the number of days since the start of the pandemic/first-measurement
  " + s(days_since_last_vac) ", #days since the last vaccination, defined by the stage the measurement was taken at
  " + n_risk_gps ", #main exposure - number of QCOVID risk groups
  " + Sex + Q_BMI ", # confounding variables for Sex and BMI
  " + ",paste0(pc.modelA.vars,collapse = " + ") #other confounding from variables named and checked above
  ) 
pc.modelA.df <- pc.modelA.df %>% select(stage,all.vars(as.formula(pc.modelA.gam.formula)))
pc.modelA.gam.formula
[1] "insufficient_response ~  s(age,by=cat,k=5) + cat + s(days_since_first_measurement)  + s(days_since_last_vac)  + n_risk_gps  + Sex + Q_BMI  + prior_infection + simd2020v2_sc_quintile + immuno + shielding + ch_resident"

Do the same for the blood donors cohort

  " + s(days_since_first_measurement) ", #spline of the number of days since the start of the pandemic/first-measurement
  " + s(days_since_last_vac) ", #days since the last vaccination, defined by the stage the measurement was taken at
  " + n_risk_gps ", #main exposure - number of QCOVID risk groups

Univariate GAM construction

Use a helper function to perform the fit the data as a univariate gam (each variable individually). From these GAM objects (one per variable in the formula) we can use them to calculate unadjusted ORs

attr(pc.modelA.gamFit,'unadjusted') <- eavehelpers::calculate_unadjusted_gam(pc.modelA.df,
                                                                              as.formula(pc.modelA.gam.formula))
